03812nam a22006015i 9780691258874DE-B159720240306124542.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t20232007nju    fo  d z      eng d  a97806912588747 a10.1515/97806912588742doi  a(DE-B1597)677686  a(OCoLC)1414456317  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anjucUS-NJ 4aN6250b.M22 2007 7aART0150702bisacsh04a745.09495/09022221 aMaguire, Eunice Dauterman, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aOther Icons :bArt and Power in Byzantine Secular Culture /cHenry Maguire, Eunice Dauterman Maguire. 1aPrinceton, NJ : bPrinceton University Press, c[2023] 4cÂ©2007  a1 online resource (224 p.) :b8 color + 150 b/w illus.  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tList of Illustrations -- tIntroduction -- t1. Novelties and Inventions in Byzantine Art -- t2. The Marvels of the Court -- t3. Animals and Magic in Byzantine Art -- t4. Byzantine Art and the Nude -- t5. Decorum, Merrymaking, and Disorder -- tConclusion -- tNotes -- tFrequently Cited Sources -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aA winged centaur with the spotted body of a leopard playing a lute; a naked man with an animal head; a goat-footed Pan; a four-bodied lion; sphinxes, and hippocamps. Few would associate these forms of art with the Byzantine era, a period dominated by religious art. However, an art of strikingly secular expression was not only common to Byzantine culture, but also key to defining it.In Other Icons, Eunice Dauterman Maguire and Henry Maguire offer the first comprehensive view of this ";unofficial"; Byzantine art, demonstrating the role it played and its dialogue with traditional Christian Byzantine art. This beautifully illustrated book creates an entirely new understanding of the whole of Byzantine art and culture.With its wide-ranging examples, the book vividly demonstrates how the surprise of this ";profane"; art is not only in its subjects of mythic creatures, exotic imagery, and eroticism, but also in the ubiquity and beauty of their placement--within churches and without, woven into silk, illuminated on manuscripts, engraved into pottery, painted in frescoes, and taking life in marble, bone, and ivory.By presenting and exploring this profane art for the first time in a scholarly book in English, Other Icons will change the way we look at the art of an entire era.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aArt, Byzantine. 0aDecorative arts, Medieval. 7aART / History / Medieval.2bisacsh1 aMaguire, Henry, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut40uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780691258874?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780691258874423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780691258874/original  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_MUAR  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_MUAR  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles